\insrsid14111555\charrsid4527623  then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9445534 DL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14111555\charrsid4527623 
Oh by that time - I was playing football for Park Avenue. Yes. And my - 1905/6 to - the beginning of the first world war and I joined up. And I joined the Royal Artillery. I was in the Field Artillery to start with and th
en I - I was transferred to the garrison. And - I went up to Newcastle to join along with a - a Midland Railway booking clerk called Hawkins and there was only two of us and we got to Newcastle we fully expected to be meeting us you know. Nobody met us. W
e
 were like two lost souls. But I had sufficient knowledge of Newcastle even in those days having played there you know. We walked up to Fennon Barracks and I went into the - into the - Sergeants quarters in the office, told them who we were, we'd just cam
e
 from Leeds. Where had we to report. He said, don't ask me, I've no idea at all. Oh this is lovely. Nobody wants us, we'd better go home. Anyway - eventually got back into Newcastle and we called at a pub in - in Monument Street, had a couple of drinks. T
h
en we went down to the - eeh what do they call it - the main St Hereford Street, great big store then up at the front, massive place. It was a - it was - then, the headquarters of the Y.M.C.A. So we walked in, great big - oh tremendous place and beautiful
 
chandeliers and there was recumbent forms sleeping her and there and here - on stretchers, blankets - army blankets over them and there were fellows sweeping up with brushes about this big you know. And cleaning - cleaning oh any amount of dust, and they 
w
ere sleeping in it. So I said to Hawkins, look - we're not sleeping here. I'm not anyway, you can please yourself. So I went into the Y.M.C.A. proper then. I saw the commandant, told him who I were and wished to join in. He said, well you can - you can ha
v
e a bedroom for eighteenpence or you can have two bunks for a shilling. And - a narrow little space, a bed there and a bed here, top one. Just enough room to undress. With my usual vivid caution I put me hand in the bed. I wasn't damp, it was almost wet. 
I thought, I'm not sleeping there. So I sat on the top. I took me boots off of course. And I slept with me clothes on, I wasn't taking any risks.
\par 
